Each [Eu(oda)3]3− unit is connected to six Ca atoms through the free (non-bonded to Eu) oxygen atoms in an anti–anti configuration, forming the anionic network [CaEu(oda)3]− (
). Thus, each Ca(II) center is surrounded by six [Eu(oda)3] units in an undistorted octahedral geometry. Cubic-like holes are formed in the anionic structure (
). They are limited by alternating Ca1 and Eu atoms in the vertexes at 6.6767(1)Å, and the oda ligands, almost planar, in the faces of the cubes. The [Ca(H2O)6]2+ (which provides charge balance to the compound) and water molecules exist as guests in alternating holes of the 3D network (). This is a rare example in which isolated [Ca(H2O)6]2+ units are found in metal–organic structures. Only three of such structures are found in the literature, [Ca(H2O)6](azo)2·2H2O (azo=4′-hydroxyazobenzene-3-sulfonate) , [Ca(CN7)2(H2O)10][Ca(H2O)6](CN7)2
, and [Ca(H2O)6] [HB(mt)3]2 (B(mt)3
=tris(3-methyl-2-thioimidazolyl)borate)) .
